id2701857\delrsid5657044 I}{\insrsid2701857 t will be a face-down Wandering Ones. It remains a 2/2 colorless creature with no name, types, or abilities, and no mana cost. Its controller can\rquote t turn it face up as a special action. If an effect turns it face up, it will have the characteristics of Wandering Ones.}{\insrsid2701857\charrsid13632182 \par }{\insrsid2701857 \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 503.4. Some effects cause a permanent that\rquote s copying a permanent to copy a different permanent while remaining in play. The change doesn\rquote t trigger comes-into-play or leaves-play abilities. This also doesn\rquote t change any noncopy effects presently affecting the permanent.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Unstable Shapeshifter reads, \ldblquote Whenever a creature comes into play, Unstable Shapeshifter becomes a copy of that creature and gains this ability.\rdblquote  A Shapeshifter is affected by Giant Growth, which reads \ldblquote Target creature gets +3/+3 until end of turn.\rdblquote  If a creature comes into play later this turn, the Shapeshifter will become a copy of that creature, but it will still get +3/+3 from the Giant Growth.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 503.5. An object that comes into play \ldblquote as a copy\rdblquote  of another permanent becomes a copy as it comes into play. It doesn\rquote t come into play, and then become a copy of that permanent. If the text that\rquote s being copied includes any abilities that replace the comes-into-play event (such as \ldblquote comes into play with\rdblquote  or \ldblquote as [this] comes into play\rdblquote  abilities), those abilities will take effect. Also, any comes-into-play triggered abilities of the copy will have a chance to trigger.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Skyshroud Behemoth reads, \ldblquote Fading 2 (This creature comes into play with two fade counters on it. At the beginning of your upkeep, remove a fade counter from it. If you can\rquote t, sacrifice it.) / Skyshroud Behemoth comes into play tapped.\rdblquote  A Clone that comes into play as a copy of a Skyshroud Behemoth will also come into play tapped with two fade counters on it.\par }{\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Striped Bears reads, \ldblquote When Striped Bears comes into play, draw a card.\rdblquote  A Clone comes into play as a copy of Striped Bears. The Clone has the Bears\rquote  comes-into-play triggered ability, so the Clone\rquote s controller draws a card.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 503.6. When copying a permanent, any choices that have been made for that permanent aren\rquote t copied. Instead, if an object comes into play as a copy of another permanent, the object\rquote s controller will get to make any \ldblquote as comes into play\rdblquote  choices for it.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  A Clone comes into play as a copy of Chameleon Spirit. Chameleon Spirit reads, in part, \ldblquote As Chameleon Spirit comes into play, choose a color.\rdblquote  The Clone won\rquote t copy the color choice of the Spirit; rather, the controller of the Clone will get to make a new choice.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 503.7. Because any choices that have been made for a permanent aren\rquote t copied, sometimes a copy card will gain an ability that refers to a choice that was never made. In that case, the choice is considered to be \ldblquote zero\rdblquote  or \ldblquote undefined.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Voice of All comes into play and Unstable Shapeshifter copies it. Voice of All reads, in part, \ldblquote As Voice of All comes into play, choose a color. / Voice of All has protection from the chosen color.\rdblquote  Unstable Shapeshifter never got a chance to choose a color, because it didn\rquote t come into play as a Voice of All card, so the Shapeshifter\rquote s protection ability doesn\rquote t protect it from anything at all.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 503.8. If an ability causes a player to make a choice as a copy comes into play, the copy will \ldblquote remember\rdblquote  that choice and continue to use it for its abilities if appropriate. If the choice is not appropriate, it is considered to be \ldblquote zero\rdblquote  or \ldblquote undefined.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  A Vesuvan Doppelganger comes into play as a copy of Chameleon Spirit, and the Doppelganger\rquote s controller chooses blue. Later, the Doppelganger copies Quirion Elves. The Elves has the ability, \ldblquote \{T\}: Add one mana of the chosen color to your mana pool.\rdblquote  If the mana ability of the Doppelganger is played, it will produce blue mana.\par }{\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  A Vesuvan Doppelganger comes into play as a copy of Caller of the Hunt. Caller of the Hunt reads, in part, \ldblquote As Caller of the Hunt comes into play, choose a creature type.\rdblquote  The Doppelganger\rquote s controller chooses Goblin. Later, the Doppelganger copies Quirion Elves. If the mana ability of the Doppelganger is played, it will fail to produce any mana. It won\rquote t produce Goblin mana.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 503.9. Some copy effects give an ability to the copy as part of the copying process. This ability becomes part of the copiable values for the copy, along with any other abilities that were copied. Also, some copy effects specifically state that they don\rquote t copy certain characteristics; they retain their original values instead.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Quirion Elves comes into play and an Unstable Shapeshifter copies it. The copiable values of the Shapeshifter now match those of the Elves, except that the Shapeshifter also has the ability \ldblquote Whenever a creature comes into play, Unstable Shapeshifter becomes a copy of that creature and gains this ability.\rdblquote  Then a Clone comes into play as a copy of the Unstable Shapeshifter. The Clone copies the new copiable values of the Shapeshifter, including the ability that the Shapeshifter gave itself when it copied the Elves.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 503.10. To copy a spell means to put a copy of the spell onto the stack; a copy of a spell isn\rquote t \ldblquote played.\rdblquote  In addition to copying the characteristics of the spell, all decisions made when the spell was played are copied. These include mode, targets, the value of X, and optional additional costs such as buyback. (See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote ) Choices that are normally made on resolution are not copied. If an effect of the copy refers to objects used to pay its costs, it uses the objects used to pay the costs of the original spell. A copy of a spell is controlled by the player who put it on the stack. A copy of a spell is itself a spell, but it has no spell card associated with it. It works just like a normal spell: it can be countered or it can resolve, and it uses the same timing rules as normal spells.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  A player plays Fork, targeting an Emerald Charm. Fork reads, \ldblquote Put a copy of target instant or sorcery spell onto the stack, except that it copies Fork\rquote s color and you may choose new targets for the copy.\rdblquote  Emerald Charm reads, \ldblquote Choose one \emdash  Untap target permanent; or destroy target non-Aura enchantment; or target creature loses flying until end of turn.\rdblquote  When the Fork resolves, it puts a copy of the Emerald Charm on the stack. The copy has the same mode that was chosen for the original Emerald Charm. It does not necessarily have the same target, but only because Fork allows choosing of new targets.\par }{\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Fling is an instant that reads, \ldblquote As an additional cost to play Fling, sacrifice a creature. / Fling deals damage equal to the sacrificed creature\rquote s power to target creature or player.\rdblquote  When determining how much damage a copy of Fling deals, it checks the power of the creature sacrificed to pay for the original Fling.}{\b\insrsid2701857 \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 503.10a A copy of a spell in a zone other than the stack ceases to exist. A copy of a card in any zone other than the stack or the in-play zone ceases to exist. This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 503.11. If an effect refers to a permanent by name, the effect still tracks that permanent even if it changes names or becomes a copy of something else.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  An Unstable Shapeshifter copies a Crazed Armodon. Crazed Armodon reads, \ldblquote \{G\}: Crazed Armodon gets +3/+0 and gains trample until end of turn. Destroy Crazed Armodon at end of turn. Play this ability only once each turn.\rdblquote  If this activated ability of the Shapeshifter is played, the Shapeshifter will be destroyed at end of turn, even if it\rquote s no longer a copy of Crazed Armodon at that time.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 503.12. An effect that instructs a player to \ldblquote play a copy\rdblquote  of an object follows the rules for playing spells and abilities, except that the copy is played while another spell or ability is resolving. Playing a copy of a nonland object follows steps 409.1a-409.1h of rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities," then the copy becomes played. The played copy is a spell on the stack, and just like any other spell it can resolve or be countered.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 504. Face-Down Spells and Permanents\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 504.1. Two cards (Illusionary Mask and Ixidron) and the morph ability (see rule 502.26) allow spells and permanents to be face down.\par \par 504.2. Face-down spells on the stack, face-down permanents in play, and face-down cards in the phased-out zone have no characteristics other than those listed by the ability or rules that allowed the card, spell, or permanent to be turned face down. Any listed characteristics are the copiable values of that object\rquote s characteristics. (See rule 418.5, \ldblquote Interaction of Continuous Effects,\rdblquote  and rule 503, \ldblquote Copying Objects.\rdblquote ) Objects that are put into play face down are turned face down before they come into play, so the permanent\rquote s comes-into-play abilities won\rquote t trigger (if triggered) or have any effect (if static). Objects that are played face down are turned face down before they are put onto the stack, so effects that care about the characteristics of a spell will see only the face-down spell\rquote s characteristics.\par \par 504.3. {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK15}{\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK40}At any time, you may look at a face-down spell you control on the stack, a face-down permanent you control, or a face-down card in the phased-out zone you controlled when it phased out. {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK15}You can\rquote t look at face-down cards in any other zone, face-down spells or permanents controlled by another player, or face-down cards in the phased-out zone last controlled by another player.{\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK40} The ability or rules that allow a permanent to be face down may also allow the permanent\rquote s controller to turn it face up. Spells normally can\rquote t be turned face up.\par \par 504.4. If you control multiple face-down spells on the stack or face-down permanents in play, you must ensure at all times that your face-down spells and permanents can be easily differentiated from each other. This includes, but is not limited to, knowing the order spells were played, the order that face-down permanents came into play, which creature attacked last turn, and any other differences between face-down spells or permanents. Common methods for distinguishing between face-down objects include using counters or dice to mark the different objects, or clearly placing those objects in order on the table.\par \par 504.5. As a face-down permanent is turned face up, its copiable values revert to its normal copiable values. Any effects that have been applied to the face-down permanent still apply to the face-up permanent. Any abilities relating to the permanent coming into play don\rquote t trigger and don\rquote t have any effect, because the permanent has already come into play.\par \par 504.6. If a face-down permanent moves from the in-play zone to any zone other than the phased-out zone, its owner must reveal it to all players as he or she moves it. If a phased-out face-down object moves to any zone other than the in-play zone, its owner must reveal it as he or she moves it. If a face-down spell moves from the stack to any zone other than the in-play zone, its owner must reveal it to all players as he or she moves it. At the end of each game, all face-down objects in play, in the phased-out zone, or on the stack must be revealed to all players.\par \par 504.7. If a face-down permanent becomes a copy of another permanent, its copiable values become the copiable values of that permanent, as modified by its face-down status. Its characteristics therefore remain the same: the characteristics listed by the ability or rules that allowed it to be turned face down. However, if it is turned face up, its copiable values become the values it copied from the other permanent.\par \par 504.8. If a face-down permanent would have an \ldblquote As [this permanent] is turned face up . . .\rdblquote  ability after it\rquote s turned face up, that ability is applied while that permanent is being turned face up, not afterward.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK11}505. Split Cards\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 505.1. Split cards have two card faces on a single card. The back of a split card is the normal }{\b\insrsid2701857 Magic: The Gathering }{\insrsid2701857 card back.\par \par 505.2. In every zone except the stack, split cards have two sets of characteristics and two converted mana costs. As long as a split card is a spell on the stack, only the characteristics of the half being played exist. The other half\rquote s characteristics are treated as though they didn\rquote t exist.\par \par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0\pararsid2701857 {\insrsid2701857 505.3. Because every split card consists of two halves with different colored mana symbols in their mana costs, each split card is a multicolored card while it\rquote s not a spell on the stack. While it\rquote s a spell on the stack, it\rquote s only the color or colors of the half being played.\par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 {\insrsid2701857 \par 505.4. Although split cards have two playable halves, each split card is only one card. For example, a player who has drawn or discarded a split card has drawn or discarded one card, not two.\par \par 505.5. An effect that asks for a particular characteristic of a split card while it\rquote s in a zone other than the stack gets two answers (one for each of the split card\rquote s two halves).\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Infernal Genesis has an ability that reads, \ldblquote At the beginning of each player\rquote s upkeep, that player puts the top card from his or her library into his or her graveyard. He or she then puts X 1/1 black Minion creature tokens into play, where X is that card\rquote s converted mana cost.\rdblquote  If the top card of your library is Assault/Battery when this ability resolves, the game sees its converted mana cost as \ldblquote 1, and 4.\rdblquote  You get five creature tokens.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0\pararsid2701857 {\insrsid2701857 505.6. An effect that performs a positive comparison (such as asking if a card is red) or a relative comparison (such as asking if a card\rquote s converted mana cost is less than 2) involving characteristics of one or more split cards in any zone other than the stack gets only one answer. This answer is }{\insrsid2701857\delrsid5264110 \ldblquote }{\insrsid2701857 yes\rdblquote  if either side of each split card in the comparison would return a \ldblquote yes\rdblquote  answer if compared individually.\par           An effect that performs a negative comparison (such as asking if cards have different names) involving characteristics of one or more split cards in any zone other than the stack also gets only one answer. This answer is \ldblquote yes\rdblquote  if performing the comparable positive comparison would return a }{\insrsid2701857\delrsid5264110 \ldblquote }{\insrsid2701857 no\rdblquote  answer.\par           If an effect performs a comparison involving multiple characteristics of one or more split cards in any zone other than the stack, each characteristic is compared separately. If each of the individual comparisons would return a \ldblquote yes\rdblquote  answer, the whole comparison returns a \ldblquote yes\rdblquote  answer.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0\pararsid2701857 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Void reads, \ldblquote Choose a number. Destroy all artifacts and creatures with converted mana cost equal to that number. Then target player reveals his or her hand and discards all nonland cards with converted mana cost equal to the number.\rdblquote  If a player plays Void and chooses 1, his or her opponent would discard Assault/Battery because the game sees its converted mana cost as \ldblquote 1, and 4.\rdblquote  The same is true if the player chooses 4. If the player chooses 5, however, Assault/Battery would be unaffected.\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 505.7. If an effect instructs a player to name a card and the player wants to name a split card, the player must name both halves of the split card.\par {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK11}\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 506. Subgames\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 506.1. {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK19}Some cards allow players to play a }{\b\insrsid2701857 Magic}{\insrsid2701857  subgame.{\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK19} A \ldblquote subgame\rdblquote  is the game created by the card\rquote s effect. The \ldblquote main game\rdblquote  is the game in which{\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK57} the spell or ability that created the subgame{\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK57} was played. The main game is temporarily discontinued while the subgame is in progress. It resumes when the subgame ends.\par \par 506.2. Any main-game abilities that trigger while the subgame is in progress aren\rquote t put onto the stack until the subgame is completed.\par \par 506.3. To start the subgame, each player removes his or her library from the game face down. It becomes that player\rquote s deck in the subgame. Abilities that trigger on cards being removed from the main game face down will trigger.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 506.3a A player\rquote s deck in the subgame may have less than the minimum number of cards. If a player\rquote s deck contains less than seven cards, the player will lose the game as soon as it starts, even if he or she mulligans. (See rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects.\rdblquote )\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 506.4. The subgame proceeds like a normal game. Randomly determine which player goes first.\par \par {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK36}506.5. All objects in the main game and all cards outside the main game are considered outside the subgame (except those specifically brought into the subgame). All players not currently in the subgame are considered outside the subgame.\par {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK36}\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 506.5a Some effects can bring cards into a game from outside of it. Cards brought into a subgame from a main game are considered to be removed from the main game. Abilities in the main game that trigger on objects being removed from the main game will trigger.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 506.6. At the end of a subgame, each player puts all objects he or she owns that were brought into the subgame into his or her library in the main game, then shuffles that library. Cards removed from the game in the subgame are not put into the player\rquote s main-game library. Instead they remain removed from the game in the main game.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  If a card was brought into the subgame either from the main game or from outside the main game, that card will be put into its owner\rquote s main-game library when the subgame ends.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 506.7. If another subgame is created during a subgame, there can be multiple subgames and main games. Each main game has one subgame, and each subgame has one main game. In this case, some games will be considered both a main game and a subgame at the same time.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 507. Controlling Another Player\rquote s Turn\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 507.1. One card (Mindslaver) allows a player\rquote s turn to be controlled by another player. This effect applies to the next turn that the affected player actually takes. The entire turn is controlled; the effect doesn\rquote t end until the beginning of the next turn.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 507.1a Multiple turn-controlling effects that affect the same player overwrite each other. The last one to be created is the one that works.\par \par 507.1b If a turn is skipped, any pending turn-controlling effects wait until the player who would be affected actually takes a turn.\par \par 507.1c Only the control of the turn changes. All objects are controlled by their normal controllers.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 507.2. If information about an object would be visible to the player whose turn is controlled, it\rquote s visible to both that player and the controller of the turn.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  The controller of a player\rquote s turn can see that player\rquote s hand and the identity of any face-down creatures he or she controls.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 507.3. The controller of another player\rquote s turn makes all choices and decisions that player is allowed to make or is told to make during that turn by the rules or by any objects. This includes choices and decisions about what to play, and choices and decisions called for by spells and abilities.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  The controller of the turn decides which spells to play and what those spells target, and makes any required decisions when those spells resolve.\par }{\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  The controller of the turn decides which of the player\rquote s creatures attack, and how those creatures assign their combat damage.\par }{\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  The controller of the turn decides which card the player chooses from outside the game with one of the }{\i0\insrsid2701857 Judgment\u8482\'aa}{\insrsid2701857  Wishes. The player can\rquote t choose a card of the wrong type.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 507.3a The controller of another player\rquote s turn can use only that player\rquote s resources (cards, mana, and so on) to pay costs for that player.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  If the controller of the turn decides that the player will play a spell with an additional cost of discarding cards, the cards are discarded from the player\rquote s hand.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 507.3b The controller of another player\rquote s turn can\rquote t make that player concede. A player may concede the game at any time, even if his or her turn is controlled by another player. See rule 102.3a.\par \par 507.3c The controller of another player\rquote s turn can\rquote t make choices or decisions for that player that aren\rquote t called for by the rules or by any objects. The controller also can\rquote t make any choices or decisions for the player that would be called for by the tournament rules.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example: }{\insrsid2701857 The player whose turn it is still chooses whether he or she leaves to visit the restroom, trades a card to someone else, takes an intentional draw, or calls a judge about an error or infraction.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 507.3d A player who controls another player\rquote s turn also continues to make his or her own choices and decisions.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 507.4. A player doesn\rquote t lose life due to mana burn while another player controls his or her turn. (Unused mana in players\rquote  mana pools is still lost when a phase ends. See rule 300.3.)\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 508. Flip Cards\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 508.1. Flip cards have a two-part card frame on a single card. The text that appears right side up on the card defines the card\rquote s normal characteristics. Additional alternative characteristics appear upside down on the card. The back of a flip card is the normal }{\b\insrsid2701857 Magic: The Gathering}{\insrsid2701857  card back.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 508.1a The top half of a flip card contains the card\rquote s normal name, text box, type line, power, and toughness. The text box usually contains an ability that causes the permanent to \ldblquote flip\rdblquote  if certain conditions are met.\par \par 508.1b The bottom half of a flip card contains an alternative name, text box, type line, power, and toughness. These characteristics are used only if the permanent is in play and only if the permanent is flipped.\par \par 508.1c A flip card\rquote s color, mana cost, expansion symbol, illustration credit, and legal text don\rquote t change if the permanent is flipped. Also, any changes to it by external effects will still apply.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 508.2. In every zone other than the in-play zone, and also in the in-play zone before the permanent flips, a flip card has only the normal characteristics of the permanent. Once the flip permanent in the in-play zone is flipped, the normal name, text box, type line, power, and toughness of the flip permanent don\rquote t apply and the alternative versions of those characteristics apply instead.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example: }{\insrsid2701857 Akki Lavarunner is a nonlegendary creature that flips into a legendary creature named Tok-Tok, Volcano Born. An effect that says \ldblquote search for library for a legendary card\rdblquote  can\rquote t find this flip card. An effect that says \ldblquote legendary creatures get +2/+2\rdblquote  doesn\rquote t affect Akki Lavarunner, but it does affect Tok-Tok.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 508.3. If you control a flip permanent, you must ensure that it\rquote s clear at all times whether the permanent is flipped or not, both when it\rquote s untapped and when it\rquote s tapped. Common methods for distinguishing between flipped and unflipped permanents include using coins or dice to mark flipped objects.\par \par 508.4. Flipping a permanent is a one-way process. Once a permanent is flipped, it\rquote s impossible for it to become unflipped. However, if a flipped permanent leaves play, it retains no memory of its status.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 509. Ending the Turn\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 509.1. One card (Time Stop) ends the turn when it resolves. When an effect ends the turn, follow these steps in order, as they differ from the normal process for resolving spells and abilities (see rule 413, \ldblquote Resolving Spells and Abilities\rdblquote ).\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 509.1a Remove every object on the stack from the game. Remove all attacking and blocking creatures, if any, from combat. All objects not in play or on the stack that aren\rquote t represented by cards will cease to exist the next time state-based effects are checked (see rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects).\par \par 509.1b Check state-based effects. No player gets priority, and no triggered abilities are put onto the stack.\par \par 509.1c The current phase and/or step ends. The game skips straight to the cleanup step. Skip any phases or steps between this phase or step and the cleanup step.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 509.2. No player gets priority during this process, so triggered abilities are not put onto the stack. If any triggered abilities have triggered between the spell or ability resolving and the cleanup step ending, there\rquote s a chance to play spells and abilities in the cleanup step. Then there will be another cleanup step before the turn finally ends (see rule 314.3).\par \par 509.3. Even though the turn ends, \ldblquote at end of turn\rdblquote  triggered abilities don\rquote t trigger because the end of turn step is skipped.\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f4\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par }{\b0\fs20\insrsid2701857 510. Status\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 510.1. A permanent\rquote s \ldblquote status\rdblquote  is its physical state. There are three status categories, each of which has two possible values: tapped/untapped, flipped/unflipped, and face up/face down. Each permanent always has one of these values for each of these categories.\par \par 510.2. Status is not a characteristic, though it may affect a permanent\rquote s characteristics.\par \par 510.3. Permanents come into play untapped, unflipped, and face up unless a spell or ability says otherwise.\par \par 510.4. A permanent retains its status until a spell, ability, or game action changes it, even if that status is not relevant to it.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857\charrsid13632182 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Dimir Doppelganger says \ldblquote \{1\}\{U\}\{B\}: Remove target creature card in a graveyard from the game. Dimir Doppelganger becomes a copy of that card and gains this ability.\rdblquote  It becomes a copy of Jushi Apprentice, a flip card. Through use of Jushi Apprentice\rquote s ability, this creature flips, making it a copy of Tomoya the Revealer with the Dimir Doppelganger ability. If this permanent then becomes a copy of Grizzly Bears, it will retain its flipped status even though that has no relevance to Grizzly Bears. If its copy ability is activated again, this time targeting a Nezumi Shortfang card (another flip card), this permanent\rquote s flipped status means it will have the characteristics of Stabwhisker the Odious (the flipped version of Nezumi Shortfang) with the Dimir Doppelganger ability.\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f4\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b0\fs20\insrsid2701857 \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 510.5. Only permanents have status. Cards not in play do not. Although a card in the removed-from-the-game zone may be face down, this has no correlation to the face-down status of a permanent.\par \par 510.6. A permanent that phases out remembers its status, as well as other information about the permanent (such as who controls it or whether it has any counters on it). It will phase in with the same status it had when it phased out. If it was face down when it phased out, it will stay face down in the phased-out zone.\par }\pard \s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 {\insrsid2701857 \par 511. Flipping a Coin\par \par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0\pararsid2701857 {\insrsid2701857 511.1. To flip a coin for an object that cares whether a player wins or loses the flip, the affected player flips the coin and calls \ldblquote heads\rdblquote  or \ldblquote tails.\rdblquote  If the call matches the result, that player wins the flip. Otherwise, the player loses the flip. Only the player who flips the coin wins or loses the flip; no other players are involved.\par \par 511.2. To flip a coin for an object that cares whether the coin comes up heads or tails, each affected player flips a coin without making a call. No player wins or loses this kind of flip.\par \par 511.3. If the coin that\rquote s being flipped doesn\rquote t have an obvious \ldblquote heads\rdblquote  or \ldblquote tails,\rdblquote  designate one side to be \ldblquote heads,\rdblquote  and the other side to be \ldblquote tails.\rdblquote  Other methods of randomization may be substituted for flipping a coin as long as there are two possible outcomes of equal likelihood and all players agree to the substitution. For example, the player may roll an even-sided die and call \ldblquote odds\rdblquote  or \ldblquote evens,\rdblquote  or roll an even-sided die and designate that \ldblquote odds\rdblquote  means \ldblquote heads\rdblquote  and \ldblquote evens\rdblquote  means \ldblquote tails.\rdblquote \par }\pard \s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 {\insrsid2701857 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\pnrauth1\pnrdate1722063963\pnrnot1\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \page 6. Multiplayer Rules\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f4\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 600. General\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 600.1. A multiplayer game is a game that begins with more than two players. This section contains additional optional rules that can be used for multiplayer play.\par \par 600.2. These rules consist of a series of options that can be added to a multiplayer game and a number of variant styles of multiplayer play. A single game may use multiple options but only one variant.\par \par 600.3. Many multiplayer }{\b\insrsid2701857 Magic}{\insrsid2701857  tournaments have additional rules not included here, including rules for deck construction. See the most current }{\b\insrsid2701857 Magic: The Gathering}{\insrsid2701857  DCI Floor Rules for more information. They can be found at }{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst {\b\insrsid2701857 HYPERLINK "http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dci/doccenter/home"}{\b\insrsid2701857 {\*\datafield 00d0c9ea79f9bace118c8200aa004ba90b0200000003000000e0c9ea79f9bace118c8200aa004ba90b7000000068007400740070003a002f002f007700770077002e00770069007a0061007200640073002e0063006f006d002f00640065006600610075006c0074002e006100730070003f0078003d006400630069002f0064006f006300630065006e007400650072002f0068006f006d0065000000}}}{\fldrslt {\cs22\b\ul\cf2\insrsid2701857 www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dci/doccenter/home}}}{\insrsid2701857 .\par \par 600.4. Unlike two-player games, multiplayer games can continue after one or more players have left the game.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK39}600.4a. When a player leaves the game, all objects (see rule 200.8) owned by that player leave the game, all spells and abilities controlled by that player on the stack cease to exist, and any change-of-control effects which give that player control of any objects end. Then, if there are any objects still controlled by that player, those objects leave the game. (Any objects leaving the game this way that aren\rquote t owned by the player leaving the game are placed in the removed-from-the-game zone.) This is not a state-based effect. It happens as soon as the player leaves the game. A player leaving the game doesn\rquote t affect combat damage on the stack.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK39}Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Alex plays Control Magic, an Aura that reads, \ldblquote }{\cf1\insrsid2701857 You control enchanted creature,\rdblquote  }{\insrsid2701857 on Bianca\rquote s Wall of Wood. If Alex leaves the game, so does Control Magic, and Wall of Wood reverts to Bianca\rquote s control. If, instead, Bianca leaves the game, so does Wall of Wood, and Control Magic is put into Alex\rquote s graveyard.\par }{\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Alex plays Threaten, which reads, in part, \ldblquote }{\cf1\insrsid2701857 Untap target creature and gain control of it until end of turn,\rdblquote }{\insrsid2701857  targeting Bianca\rquote s Wall of Wood. If Alex leaves the game, Threaten\rquote s change-of-control effect ends and Wall of Wood reverts to Bianca\rquote s control.\par }{\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Alex plays Bribery, which reads, \ldblquote }{\cf1\insrsid2701857 Search target opponent\rquote s library for a creature card and put that card into play under your control. Then that player shuffles his or her library,\rdblquote }{\insrsid2701857  targeting Bianca. Alex puts Wall of Wood into play from Bianca\rquote s library. If Alex leaves the game, Wall of Wood leaves the game. If, instead, Bianca leaves the game, Wall of Wood still leaves the game.\par }{\b\insrsid2701857 {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK41}Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Alex controls Genesis Chamber, which reads, \ldblquote }{\cf1\insrsid2701857 Whenever a nontoken creature comes into play, if Genesis Chamber is untapped, that creature\rquote s controller puts a 1/1 Myr artifact creature token into play.\rdblquote  }{\insrsid2701857 If Alex leaves the game, all Myr tokens created by Genesis Chamber while it was under Alex\rquote s control leave the game as well because Alex owns the tokens.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK41}\par 600.4b. If an object would change to the control of a player who has left the game, that object\rquote s control remains unchanged. If a token would be put into play under the control of a player who has left the game, no token is created.\par \par {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK43}600.4c If an object owned by a player who has left the game would be put into any zone, it leaves the game instead. (This includes abilities that would be put onto the stack.)\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK42}Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Astral Slide is an enchantment that reads, \ldblquote }{\cf1\insrsid2701857 Whenever a player cycles a card, you may remove target creature from the game. If you do, return that creature to play under its owner\rquote s control at end of turn.\rdblquote  }{\insrsid2701857 During Alex\rquote s turn, Bianca uses Astral Slide\rquote s ability to remove Alex\rquote s Hypnotic Specter from the game. Before the end of that turn, Bianca leaves the game. At end of turn, the delayed triggered ability generated by Astral Slide that would return Hypnotic Specter to play triggers, but it leaves the game rather than being put on the stack. Hypnotic Specter never returns to play.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK43}{\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK42}\par 600.4d If an object requires a player who has left the game to make a choice, the controller of the object chooses another player to make that choice. If the original choice was to be made by an opponent of the controller of the object, that player chooses another opponent if possible.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 601. Limited Range of Influence Option\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 601.1. Limited range of influence is an option that can be applied to most multiplayer games. It\rquote s always used in the Emperor variant (see rule 607), and it\rquote s often used for games involving five or more players.\par \par 601.2. A player\rquote s range of influence is the maximum distance from that player, measured in player seats, that the player can affect. Players within that many seats of the player are within that player\rquote s range of influence. Objects controlled by players within a player\rquote s range of influence are also within that player\rquote s range of influence. Range of influence covers spells, abilities, effects, damage dealing, attacking, and making choices. \par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 601.2a The most commonly chosen limited ranges of influence are 1 seat and 2 seats. Different players may have different ranges of influence.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  A range of influence of 1 means that only you and the players seated directly next to you are within your range of influence.\par }{\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  A range of influence of 2 means that you and the two players to your left and the two players to your right are within your range of influence.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 601.2b A player is always within his or her own range of influence.\par \par 601.2c The particular players within each player\rquote s range of influence are determined as each turn begins. \par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  In a game with a range of influence of 1, Alex is seated to the left of Rob, and Carissa is seated to the right of Rob. Carissa is not in Alex\rquote s range of influence. If Rob leaves the game, Carissa will enter Alex\rquote s range of influence at the start of the next turn.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 601.2d An object is within a player\rquote s range of influence if it\rquote s controlled by that player or by another player within that many seats of that player.\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 601.3. Creatures can attack only opponents within their controller\rquote s range of influence. If no opponents are within a player\rquote s range of influence, creatures that player controls can\rquote t attack.\par \par 601.4. Objects and players outside a player\rquote s range of influence can\rquote t be the targets of spells or abilities that player controls.\par \par 601.5. Some cards require players to make choices. These cards work differently when the limited range of influence option is used.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 601.5a If a player is asked to choose an object or player, he or she must choose one within his or her range of influence.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  In a game with a range of influence of 1, Alex is seated to the left of Rob. Alex activates the ability of Cuombajj Witches, which reads, \ldblquote }{\cf1\insrsid2701857 Cuombajj Witches deals 1 damage to target creature or player and 1 damage to target creature or player of an opponent\rquote s choice,\rdblquote  targeting Rob and choosing Rob as the opponent who picks the other target. Rob }{\insrsid2701857 must choose a target that\rquote s in both his range of influence and in the range of influence of the controller of Cuombajj Witches. He must therefore choose himself, Alex, or a creature controlled by either himself or Alex.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 601.5b If a player is asked to choose between one or more options (and not between one or more objects or players), he or she can choose between those options even if those options refer to objects or players outside the player\rquote s range of influence.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Alex, who has a range of influence of 2, is seated to the left of Rob, and Carissa, who has range of influence of 1, is seated to the right of Rob. Alex plays a card that reads, \ldblquote An opponent chooses one \emdash  You draw 2 cards; or each creature you control gets +2/+2 until end of turn,\rdblquote  and chooses Carissa to make that choice. Carissa can choose the mode even though Alex is out of her range.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 601.5c If an effect requires a choice and there\rquote s no player who can make that choice within its controller\rquote s range of influence, the closest appropriate player to its controller\rquote s left makes that choice.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  In an Emperor game in which all players have range of influence 1, an emperor plays Fact or Fiction, which reads, \ldblquote Reveal the top five cards of your library. An opponent separates those cards into two piles. Put one pile into your hand and the other into your graveyard.\rdblquote  Since no opponent is within the emperor\rquote s range of influence, the nearest opponent to the emperor\rquote s left separates the cards into piles.\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 601.6. A player can\rquote t play the activated abilities of an object outside of his or her range of influence.\par \par 601.7. A triggered ability doesn\rquote t trigger unless its trigger event happens entirely within the range of influence of its source\rquote s controller.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  In a game with range of influence limited to 1, Alex is seated to the left of Rob. Rob controls two Auras attached to Alex\rquote s Grizzly Bears: One with the trigger condition \ldblquote Whenever enchanted creature becomes blocked,\rdblquote  and one with the trigger condition \ldblquote Whenever enchanted creature becomes blocked by a creature.\rdblquote  Alex\rquote s Grizzly Bears attacks the player to Alex\rquote s left and becomes blocked. The ability of Rob\rquote s first Aura triggers because the entire event (Grizzly Bears becomes blocked) happens within Rob\rquote s range of influence. The ability of Rob\rquote s second Aura doesn\rquote t trigger, however, because that event includes the blocking creature, which is out of Rob\rquote s range.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 601.7a If a trigger event includes an object moving out of or into a player\rquote s range of influence, use the game state before or after the event as appropriate to determine whether the triggered ability will trigger. See rule 410.10.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Carissa and Alex are outside each other\rquote s range of influence. Carissa controls a creature owned by Alex and they each control a Soul Net, an artifact which reads, \ldblquote }{\cf1\insrsid2701857 Whenever a creature is put into a graveyard from play, you may pay \{1\}. If you do, you gain 1 life.\rdblquote }{\insrsid2701857  The creature is destroyed and is put into Alex\rquote s graveyard. Alex\rquote s Soul Net doesn\rquote t trigger because the destruction event was outside Alex\rquote s range of influence. Carissa\rquote s Soul Net does trigger, even though the creature is going to a graveyard outside her range, because the destruction event was within her range.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 601.8. An Aura can\rquote t enchant an object outside its controller\rquote s range of influence. If an Aura is attached to an illegal permanent, the Aura is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard as a state-based effect. See rule 420.\par \par 601.9. An Equipment can\rquote t equip an object outside its controller\rquote s range of influence. If an Equipment is attached to an illegal permanent, it becomes unattached from that permanent but remains in play. This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 601.10. Spells and abilities can\rquote t affect objects or players outside their controller\rquote s range of influence. The parts of the effect that attempt to affect an out-of-range object or player will do nothing. The rest of the effect will work normally.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  In a six-player game where each player has range of influence 1, Alex plays Pyroclasm, which reads, \ldblquote Pyroclasm deals 2 damage to each creature.\rdblquote  Pyroclasm deals 2 damage to each creature controlled by Alex, the player to Alex\rquote s left, and the player to Alex\rquote s right. No other creatures are dealt damage.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 601.11. If a spell or ability requires information from the game, it gets only information from within its controller\rquote s range of influence. It doesn\rquote t see objects or events outside its controller\rquote s range of influence.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  In a six-player game where each player has range of influence 1, Alex controls Coat of Arms, which reads, \ldblquote }{\cf1\insrsid2701857 Each creature gets +1/+1 for each other creature in play that shares a creature type with it.\rdblquote  }{\insrsid2701857 Coat of Arms will boost Alex\rquote s creatures based only on what creatures are controlled by Alex, the player to Alex\rquote s left, and the player to Alex\rquote s right. It won\rquote t take other creatures into account.\par }{\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  In the same game, Rob is sitting to the right of Alex. Coat of Arms will boost Rob\rquote s creatures based only on what creatures are controlled by Rob and Alex. They are the only two players within range of both Rob and the controller of Coat of Arms.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 601.12. The \ldblquote legend rule\rdblquote  (see rule 420.5e) applies to a permanent only if other legendary permanents with the same name are within its controller\rquote s range of influence.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example: }{\insrsid2701857 Alex has range of influence 1, and Carissa has range of influence 2. Rob sits between them. If Alex controls a legendary permanent and Carissa puts a legendary permanent with the same name into play, only the one controlled by Carissa will be put into a graveyard.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 601.13. The \ldblquote world rule\rdblquote  (see rule 420.5i) applies to a permanent only if other world permanents are within its controller\rquote s range of influence.\par \par 601.14. Replacement and prevention effects watch for a particular event to happen and then completely or partially replace that event. The limited range of influence option can cause the modified event to contain instructions that can\rquote t be carried out, in which case the player simply ignores the impossible instructions. See rule 419, \ldblquote Replacement and Prevention Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 601.14a If a replacement effect tries to cause a spell or ability to affect an object or player outside its controller\rquote s range of influence, that portion of the event does nothing.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Alex plays Lava Axe (\ldblquote Lava Axe deals 5 damage to target player\rdblquote ) targeting Rob. In response, Rob plays Captain\rquote s Maneuver (\ldblquote }{\insrsid2701857 The next X damage that would be dealt to target creature or player this turn is dealt to another target creature or player instead.\rdblquote ) with X = 3, targeting Carissa. Carissa isn\rquote t in Alex\rquote s range of influence.}{\insrsid2701857  When Lava Axe resolves, it deals only 2 damage to Rob and no damage to Carissa.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 601.14b If a spell or ability creates an effect that prevents damage that would be dealt by a source, it can affect only sources within the spell or ability\rquote s controller\rquote s range of influence. If a spell or ability creates an effect that prevents damage that would be dealt to a creature or player, it can affect only creatures and players within the spell or ability\rquote s controller\rquote s range of influence. If a spell or ability creates an effect that prevents damage, but neither the source nor the would-be recipient of the damage is specified, it prevents damage only if both the source and recipient of that damage are within the spell or ability\rquote s controller\rquote s range of influence.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Rob is within Alex\rquote s range of influence, but Carissa is not. Alex controls an enchantment that says, \ldblquote Prevent all damage that would be dealt by creatures.\rdblquote  Carissa attacks Rob with a creature. The creature deals combat damage to Rob.\par }{\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Rob is within Alex\rquote s range of influence, but Carissa is not. Carissa plays Lightning Blast (\ldblquote Lightning Blast deals 4 damage to target creature or player\rdblquote ) targeting Rob. In response, Alex plays Honorable Passage (\ldblquote }{\insrsid2701857 The next time a source of your choice would deal damage to target creature or player this turn, prevent that damage. If damage from a red source is prevented this way, Honorable Passage deals damage equal to the damage prevented this way to the source\rquote s controller.\rdblquote ) }{\insrsid2701857 targeting Rob. The damage to Rob is prevented, but Honorable Passage can\rquote t deal damage to Carissa.\par }{\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Rob is within Alex\rquote s range of influence, but Carissa is not. Carissa attacks Rob with a creature, and Rob blocks with a creature. Alex plays Holy Day (\ldblquote Prevent all combat damage that would be dealt this turn.\rdblquote ) Carissa and Rob\rquote s creatures deal combat damage to each other.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 602. Attack Multiple Players Option\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 602.1. Some multiplayer games allow the active player to attack multiple other players. If this option is used, a player can also choose to attack only one player during a particular combat.\par \par 602.2. As the combat phase starts, the attacking player doesn\rquote t choose an opponent to become the defending player. Instead, all the attacking player\rquote s opponents are defending players during the combat phase.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 602.2a Any rule, object, or effect that refers to a \ldblquote defending player\rdblquote  refers to one specific defending player, not to all of the defending players. This will usually be the defending player that the creature with the ability is attacking; if there are multiple defending players that could be chosen, the controller of the ability chooses one.\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 602.3. As the attacking player declares each attacking creature, he or she chooses a defending player for it to attack. See rule 308, \ldblquote Declare Attackers Step.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 602.3a Restrictions and requirements that don\rquote t apply to attacking a specific player are evaluated based on the entire group of attacking creatures. Restrictions and requirements that apply to attacking a specific player apply only to creatures attacking that player. The entire group of attacking creatures must still be legal. See rule 500, \ldblquote Legal Attacks and Blocks.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  Rob attacks Alex with Grizzly Bears and attacks Carissa with a creature with mountainwalk. Whether the creature with mountainwalk is unblockable depends only on whether Carissa controls a Mountain.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 602.3b Creatures in a band can\rquote t attack different players. See rule 502.10, \ldblquote Banding.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 602.4. If creatures are attacking more than one player, each defending player declares blockers in APNAP order as the declare blockers step begins. (See rule 103.4 and rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step.\rdblquote ) The first defending player declares all his or her blocks, then the second defending player, and so on.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 602.4a A defending player can block only with creatures he or she controls. Those creatures can block only creatures attacking that player; they can\rquote t block creatures attacking other players.\par \par 602.4b When determining whether a defending player\rquote s blocks are legal, ignore any creatures attacking other players and any blocking creatures controlled by other players.\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 602.5. Combat damage is assigned in APNAP order. Other than that, the combat damage step proceeds just as in a two-player game. See rule 310, \ldblquote Combat Damage Step.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 603. Deploy Creatures Option\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 603.1. The Emperor variant always uses the deploy creatures option, and it can be used in other variants that allow players to compete in teams. Multiplayer formats in which players compete as individuals usually don\rquote t use this option.\par \par 603.2. Each creature has the ability \ldblquote \{T\}: Target teammate gains control of this creature. Play this ability only any time you could play a sorcery.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 604. Attack Left and Attack Right Options\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 604.1. Some multiplayer games use the optional }{\i\insrsid2701857 attack left}{\insrsid2701857  or}{\i\insrsid2701857  attack right}{\insrsid2701857  rules.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 604.1a If the attack left option is used, a player can attack only an opponent seated immediately to his or her left. If a player\rquote s nearest opponent to the left is more than one seat away, the player can\rquote t attack.\par \par 604.1b If the attack right option is used, a player can attack only an opponent seated immediately to his or her right. If a player\rquote s nearest opponent to the right is more than one seat away, the player can\rquote t attack.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 605. Free-for-All Variant\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 605.1 In Free-for-All multiplayer games, a group of players compete as individuals against each other.\par \par 605.2. Any multiplayer options used are determined before play begins. The Free-for-All variant uses the following default options.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 605.2a The limited range of influence option usually isn\rquote t used in Free-for-All games. If it is, each player has the same range of influence, which is determined before play begins. See rule 601, \ldblquote Limited Range of Influence Option.\rdblquote \par \par 605.2b Exactly one of the attack left, attack right, and attack multiple players options must be used. See rule 604, \ldblquote Attack Left and Attack Right Options,\rdblquote  and rule 602, \ldblquote Attack Multiple Players Option.\rdblquote \par \par 605.2c The deploy creatures option isn\rquote t used in the Free-for-All variant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 605.3. The players are randomly seated around the table.\par \par 605.4. Free-for-All games use the normal rules for winning and losing the game. See rule 102, \ldblquote Winning and Losing.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 606. Two-Headed Giant Variant\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 606.1. Two-Headed Giant games are played with two teams of two players each.\par \par 606.2. No other multiplayer options are used in Two-Headed Giant games.\par \par 606.3. Each team sits together on one side of the table. Each team decides the order in which its players sit. The player seated on the right within each team is the primary player, and the player seated on the left is the secondary player.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 606.4. The Two-Headed Giant variant has two unique features.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 606.4a Each team has a shared life total, which starts at 40 life.\par \par 606.4b. Each team takes turns rather than each player.\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 606.5. With the exception of life total, a team\rquote s resources (cards in hand, mana, and so on) are not shared in the Two-Headed Giant variant. Teammates may review each other\rquote s hands and discuss strategies at any time. Teammates can\rquote t manipulate each other\rquote s cards or permanents.}{\highlight4\insrsid2701857 \par }{\insrsid2701857 \par 606.6. Timing of Team Turns\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857\charrsid7684118 \par }{\insrsid2701857 606.6a}{\insrsid2701857\charrsid7684118  A player who is dissatisfied with his or her initial hand may mulligan. First, the starting team takes any mulligans. For a team to take a mulligan, each player on that team decides whether to shuffle his or her hand back into the deck and then draw a new hand of seven cards. All players }{\insrsid2701857 on that team }{\insrsid2701857\charrsid7684118 who chose to do so take their mulligans at the same time. After each player on that team who took a mulligan looks at his or her new hand, the team repeats the process, resulting in a hand of one fewer card each time, until the hand size reaches zero cards. Teammates may consult during this process, but a player can\rquote t see the result of his or her teammate\rquote s mulligan before deciding whether to take a mulligan at the same time. Once a player has decided to keep a hand, those cards become his or her opening hand. That player can\rquote t take any more mulligans, but his or her teammate may. Once each player on }{\insrsid2701857 the starting}{\insrsid2701857\charrsid7684118  team decides to keep an opening hand, the other team may take mulligans.\par \par }\pard \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 {\insrsid2701857 606.6b. During the draw step of the starting team\rquote s first turn, only the secondary player draws a card. The primary player does not (see rule 101.5).\par \par 606.6c Teams have priority, not individual players.\par \par {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK9}606.6d The Active Player, Nonactive Player order rule (see rule 103.4) is modified for Two-Headed Giant play. The team whose turn it is is the active team. The other team is the nonactive team. If both teams would make choices and/or take actions at the same time, first the active team makes any choices required, then the nonactive team makes any choices required. Then the actions happen simultaneously.\par {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK9}\par 606.6e A player may play a spell or activated ability, or take a special action, only when his or her team has priority. If both players on a team want to take an action at the same time, the primary player decides who takes the action. Each player on a team draws a card during that team\rquote s draw step. Each player on a team may play a land during each of that team\rquote s turns.\par \par 606.6f If neither player on a team wishes to do anything, that team passes. If both teams pass in succession (that is, if both teams pass without any player taking any actions in between passing), the top object on the stack resolves, then the active team receives priority. If the stack is empty when both teams pass in succession, the phase or step ends and the next one begins.}{\highlight4\insrsid2701857 \par }{\insrsid2701857 \par 606.6g If an effect gives a player an extra turn or adds a phase or step to that player\rquote s turn, that player\rquote s team takes the extra turn, phase, or step. If an effect causes a player to skip a step, phase, or turn, that player\rquote s team does so. If an effect causes a player to control another player\rquote s turn, the controller of that effect controls the affected player\rquote s team\rquote s turn.\par \par }\pard \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0\pararsid2701857 {\insrsid2701857 606.6h If an effect instructs more than one player to draw cards in a Two-Headed Giant game, first the primary player on the active team performs all of his or her draws, then the secondary player on that team performs all of his or her draws, then the nonactive team does the same.\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 606.7. The Two-Headed Giant variant uses different combat rules than other multiplayer variants.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK20}606.7a Each team\rquote s creatures attack the other team as a group. During the combat phase, the active team is the }{\i\insrsid2701857 attacking team}{\insrsid2701857  and each player on the active team is an attacking player. Likewise, the nonactive team is the }{\i\insrsid2701857 defending team}{\insrsid2701857  and each player on the nonactive team is a defending player.\par {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK20}\par 606.7b. As the declare attackers step begins, the active team declares attackers. If a creature is unable to attack one of the defending players, that creature can\rquote t attack the defending team. The active team has one combined attack, and that set of attacking creatures must be legal as a whole.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0\pararsid2701857 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  One player in a Two-Headed Giant game controls Teferi\rquote s Moat, which says \ldblquote As Teferi\rquote s Moat comes into play, choose a color. / Creatures of the chosen color without flying can\rquote t attack you.\rdblquote  Creatures of the chosen color without flying can\rquote t attack that player\rquote s team.}{\insrsid2701857\charrsid4140491 \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 606.7c As the declare blockers step begins, the defending team declares blockers. Creatures controlled by the defending players can block any attacking creatures. The defending team has one combined block, and that set of blocking creatures must be legal as a whole.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0\pararsid2701857 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example: }{\insrsid2701857 If an attacking creature has forestwalk and either player on the defending team controls a Forest, the creature can\rquote t be blocked.}{\insrsid2701857\charrsid4140491 \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 606.7d As the combat damage step begins, the active team announces how each attacking creature will assign its combat damage. If an attacking creature would assign combat damage to the defending team, the active team chooses only one of the defending players for that creature to assign its combat damage to. Then the defending team announces how each blocking creature will assign its combat damage.\par }{\highlight4\insrsid2701857 \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 606.8. The Two-Headed Giant variant uses the normal rules for winning or losing the game (see rule 102), with the following additions.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 606.8a If a team\rquote s life total is 0 or less, the team loses the game the next time a team would receive priority. (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)\par \par {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK12}606. 8b Players win and lose the game only as a team, not as individuals. If either player on a team loses the game, the team loses the game. If either player on a team wins the game, the entire team wins the game. If an effect would prevent a player from winning the game, that player\rquote s team can\rquote t win the game. If an effect would prevent a player from losing the game, that player\rquote s team can\rquote t lose the game.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK12}Example:}{\insrsid2701857  In a Two-Headed Giant game, a player controls Transcendence, which reads, in part, \ldblquote }{\cf1\insrsid2701857 You don\rquote t lose the game for having 0 or less life.\rdblquote  If that player\rquote s team\rquote s life total is 0 or less, that team doesn\rquote t lose the game.}{\insrsid2701857 \par }{\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  In a Two-Headed Giant game, a player attempts to draw a card while there are no cards in that player\rquote s library. That player loses the game, so that player\rquote s entire team loses the game.\par }{\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  In a Two-Headed Giant game, a player controls Platinum Angel, which reads, \ldblquote }{\cf1\insrsid2701857 You can\rquote t lose the game and your opponents can\rquote t win the game.\rdblquote  Neither that player nor his or her teammate can lose the game while Platinum Angel is in play, and neither player on the opposing team can win the game.}{\insrsid2701857 \par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 606.8c If a player concedes, his or her team loses the game.\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 606.9. Damage, loss of life, and gaining life happen to each player individually. The result is applied to the team\rquote s shared life total.\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  In a Two-Headed Giant game, a player plays Flame Rift, which reads, \ldblquote Flame Rift deals 4 damage to each player.\rdblquote  Each team is dealt a total of 8 damage.\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 \par 606.9a If an effect needs to know the value of an individual player\rquote s life total, that effect uses the team\rquote s life total divided by two, rounded up, instead.\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  In a Two-Headed Giant game, a team is at 17 life when a player activates Heartless Hidetsugu\rquote s ability, which reads, \ldblquote }{\cf1\insrsid2701857 Heartless Hidetsugu deals to each player damage equal to half that player\rquote s life total, rounded down.\rdblquote  For the purposes of this ability, each player on that team is considered to be at 9 life. Heartless Hidetsugu deals 4 damage to each of those players, for a total of 8 damage. The team will end up at 9 life.}{\insrsid2701857 \par }{\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  In a Two-Headed Giant game, a player controls Test of Endurance, an enchantment that reads, \ldblquote }{\cf1\insrsid2701857 At the beginning of your upkeep, if you have 50 or more life, you win the game.\rdblquote  At the beginning of your upkeep, the player\rquote s team wins the game only if his or her share of the team\rquote s life total is 50 or more. The team\rquote s life total must be 99 or more for that to happen.}{\insrsid2701857 \par }{\b\insrsid2701857 Example:}{\insrsid2701857  In a Two-Headed Giant game, a player controls Lurking Jackals, which reads, \ldblquote When an opponent has 10 life or less, if Lurking Jackals is an enchantment, it becomes a 3/2 Hound creature.\rdblquote  