ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 {\insrsid2701857      Landwalk is an evasion ability. A creature with landwalk is unblockable as long as the defending player controls at least one land which has the specified subtype or supertype. See rule 502.6, \ldblquote Landwalk.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Last Known Information\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 The last known information about an object is the information that it had just before it left the zone it was in. Effects from resolving spells and abilities use last known information if the object they require information from isn\rquote t in the zone it\rquote s expected to be in (unless the effect divides damage). See rule 413.2f.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Layer\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Continuous effects are applied in order, in six layers: (1) copy effects (see rule 503, \ldblquote Copying Objects\rdblquote ); (2) control-changing effects; (3) text-changing effects; (4) type-, subtype-, and supertype-changing effects; (5) all other continuous effects, except those that change power and/or toughness, and (6) power- and/or toughness-changing effects. Inside layer 6, effects are applied in a series of sublayers. See rule 418.5, \ldblquote Interaction of Continuous Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Leaves Play\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 A permanent leaves play when it moves from the in-play zone to any other zone (see rule 410.10c) or when its owner leaves the game (see rule 600.4a).\par      If a token leaves play, it ceases to exist. This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.5.\par }\pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 {\insrsid2701857      If a permanent leaves play and later returns to play, it\rquote s treated as an entirely new permanent with no \ldblquote memory\rdblquote  of anything from its former existence. (Phasing is an exception to this; see rule 502.15, \ldblquote Phasing.\rdblquote  Permanents that phase out also don\rquote t trigger any comes-into-play or leaves-play abilities.)\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Legal Text\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Legal text (the fine print at the bottom of the card) lists the copyright information. It has no effect on game play. See rule 210, \ldblquote Legal Text.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Legend (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Many creature cards were printed with the creature type \ldblquote Legend.\rdblquote  All of these cards have been given errata to have the legendary supertype. Legend is no longer a creature type. See Legendary.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Legendary\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Legendary is a supertype that may apply to any type (\ldblquote Legendary Land,\rdblquote  \ldblquote Legendary Artifact,\rdblquote  and so on).\par      If two or more legendary permanents with the same name are in play, all are put into their owners\rquote  graveyards. This \ldblquote legend rule\rdblquote  is a state-based effect. See rule 420.5.\par }\pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 {\insrsid2701857      If a legendary permanent\rquote s types or subtypes change, this doesn\rquote t change its supertypes. The permanent will still be legendary.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Lethal Damage\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Lethal damage is an amount of damage greater than or equal to a creature\rquote s toughness. A creature with lethal damage, but greater than 0 toughness, is destroyed. This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.5.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Library\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 The library is the zone from which a player draws cards. When a game begins, each player\rquote s deck becomes his or her library. See rule 217.2, \ldblquote Library.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Life, Life Total\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Life total is a sort of score. Each player starts the game with 20 life. Any increase in a player\rquote s life total is considered to be gaining life. Any decrease in a player\rquote s life total is considered to be losing life. A player whose life total drops to 0 or less loses. This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.5.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 LIFO (Informal)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 An acronym for \ldblquote Last In, First Out,\rdblquote  LIFO is the order in which spells and abilities resolve after going on the stack. The last played is resolved first. See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities,\rdblquote  and rule 413, \ldblquote Resolving Spells and Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Limited Range of Influence\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Limited range of influence is an optional rule used in some multiplayer games. A player\rquote s range of influence is the maximum distance from that player, measured in player seats, that the player can affect. Players within that many seats of the player are within that player\rquote s range of influence. Objects controlled by players within a player\rquote s range of influence are also within that player\rquote s range of influence. Range of influence covers spells, abilities, effects, damage dealing, attacking, and making choices. See rule 601, \ldblquote Limited Range of Influence Option.\rdblquote \par }\pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 {\insrsid2701857      The limited range of influence option is always used in the Emperor variant (see rule 607), and it\rquote s often used for games involving five or more players.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Local Enchantment (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Some older cards used the term \ldblquote local enchantment\rdblquote  for enchantments that are attached to other permanents while they\rquote re in play. These cards now have the Aura subtype.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Lose the Game\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 There are several ways to lose the game. A player can concede the game at any time; a player who concedes loses the game immediately. If a player\rquote s life total is 0 or less, he or she loses the game the next time a player would receive priority (this is a state-based effect; see rule 420). }{\insrsid2701857\delrsid2701857 If a}{\insrsid2701857  player attempts to draw a card from an empty library, he or she loses the game the next time a player would receive priority (this is a state-based effect; see rule 420). If a player has ten or more poison counters, he or she loses the game the next time a player would receive priority. (this is a state-based effect; see rule 420). If a player would both win and lose simultaneously, he or she loses. In a multiplayer game between teams, a team loses the game if all players on that team have lost. See rule 102, \ldblquote Winning and Losing.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Madness\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Madness is a keyword that represents two abilities. \ldblquote Madness [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote If a player would discard this card, that player discards it, but may remove it from the game instead of putting it into his or her }{\insrsid2701857\charrsid6299095 graveyard\rdblquote  and }{\insrsid2701857 \ldblquote }{\insrsid2701857\charrsid6299095 When this card is removed from the game this way, its owner may play it by paying [cost] rather than paying its mana cost. If that player doesn}{\insrsid2701857 \rquote }{\insrsid2701857\charrsid6299095 t, he or she puts this card into his or her graveyard.}{\insrsid2701857 \rdblquote }{\insrsid2701857\charrsid6299095  See}{\insrsid2701857  rule 502.24, \ldblquote Madness.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Main Game\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Some cards allow players to play a }{\b\insrsid2701857 Magic}{\insrsid2701857  subgame. The \ldblquote main game\rdblquote  is the game in which the spell or ability that created the subgame was played. See rule 506, \ldblquote Subgames.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Main Phase\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 The term \ldblquote main phase\rdblquote  comprises the first main and second main phases, also called the \ldblquote precombat\rdblquote  and \ldblquote postcombat\rdblquote  main phases. Artifact, creature, enchantment, and sorcery spells may be played only by the active player during his or her main phase, and only when the stack is empty. A player may also play one land each turn during his or her main phase.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Mana\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Mana is the energy used to play spells and is usually produced by lands. Mana is created by mana abilities (and sometimes by spells), and it can be used to pay costs immediately or can stay in the player\rquote s mana pool. See rule 406, \ldblquote Mana Abilities.\rdblquote \par      Colored mana costs, represented by colored mana symbols, can be paid only with the appropriate color of mana. Generic mana costs can be paid with any color of, or with colorless, mana. See rule 104.3.\par      The spell or ability that adds mana to a mana pool may restrict how it can be used. An ability might produce mana that can be used only to play creature spells or only to pay activation costs.\par }\pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 {\insrsid2701857      {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK2}The type of mana a permanent \ldblquote could produce\rdblquote  is the type of mana that any ability of that permanent can generate, taking into account any applicable replacement effects. If the type of mana can\rquote t be defined, there\rquote s no type of mana that that permanent could produce. The \ldblquote type\rdblquote  of mana is its color, or lack thereof (for colorless mana).{\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK2}\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Mana Ability\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 A mana ability is either activated or triggered. A mana ability doesn\rquote t go on the stack\emdash it resolves immediately. See rule 411, \ldblquote Playing Mana Abilities.\rdblquote \par }\pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 {\insrsid2701857      A player may play an activated mana ability whenever he or she has priority and whenever a rule or effect asks for a mana payment. This is the only type of ability that can be played in the middle of playing or resolving a spell or ability. See rule 406, \ldblquote Mana Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Mana Burn\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 When a phase ends, any unused mana remaining in a player\rquote s mana pool is lost. The player loses 1 life for each mana lost this way. This is called \ldblquote mana burn.\rdblquote  See rule 300.3.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Mana Cost\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 The mana cost of a card is indicated by the mana symbols printed on its upper right corner. If a card has no mana symbols printed in its upper right corner, it has no mana cost. Land cards and face-down spells and permanents normally have no mana cost. Tokens have no mana cost unless the effect that creates them specifies otherwise. A copy of an object copies that object\rquote s mana cost. See rule 203, \ldblquote Mana Cost and Color.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Mana Pool\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 When an effect creates mana, that mana goes into the player\rquote s mana pool. From there, it can be used to pay for spells and abilities. The mana can be used immediately to pay a cost, or stored in the mana pool for use later in the phase. The mana pool is cleared at the end of each phase. See also Mana Burn.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Mana Source (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Some older cards were printed with the type \ldblquote mana source.\rdblquote  All mana source cards are now instant cards. Abilities that used to read \ldblquote Play this ability as a mana source\rdblquote  are now mana abilities.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Mana Symbol\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 The mana symbols are \{W\}, \{U\}, \{B\}, \{R\}, \{G\}, \{X\}, \{Y\}, and \{Z\}; the numerals \{0\}, \{1\}, \{2\}, \{3\}, \{4\}, and so on; the hybrid symbols \{W/U\}, \{W/B\}, \{U/B\}, \{U/R\}, \{B/R\}, \{B/G\}, \{R/G\}, \{R/W\}, \{G/W\}, and \{G/U\}; and the snow symbol \{S\}. See rule 104.3.\par      Each of the colored mana symbols represents one colored mana: \{W\} white, \{U\} blue, \{B\} black, \{R\} red, and \{G\} green. See rule 104.3a.\par      Numeral symbols (such as \{1\}) are generic mana costs and represent an amount of mana that can be paid with any color of, or colorless, mana. See rule 104.3b.\par      The symbols \{X\}, \{Y\} and \{Z\} represent unspecified amounts of mana; when playing a spell or activated ability with \{X\}, \{Y\}, or \{Z\} in its cost, its controller decides the value of that variable. See rule 104.3c.\par      Numeral symbols and variable symbols can also represent colorless mana if they appear in the effect of a spell or of a mana ability that reads \ldblquote add [mana symbol] to your mana pool\rdblquote  or something similar. See rule 104.3d.\par      The symbol \{0\} represents zero mana and is used as a placeholder when a spell or activated ability costs nothing to play. A spell or ability whose cost is \{0\} must still be played the same way as one with a cost greater than zero; it won\rquote t play itself automatically. See rule 104.3e.\par }\pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 {\insrsid2701857      Each of the hybrid mana symbols represents a cost which can be paid with one of two colors: \{W/U\} in a cost can be paid with either white or blue mana, \{W/B\} white or black, \{U/B\} blue or black, \{U/R\} blue or red, \{B/R\} black or red, \{B/G\} black or green, \{R/G\} red or green, \{R/W\} red or white, \{G/W\} green or white, and \{G/U\} green or blue. See rule 104.3f.\par      The symbol \{S\} represents a cost that can be paid with one mana produced by a snow permanent. See rule 104.3h.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Match\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 A match is a series of }{\b\insrsid270185