033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Some cards give poison counters to players. If a player has ten or more poison counters, he or she loses the game the next time a player would receive priority. See rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Poly Artifact (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Some older cards used the term \ldblquote poly artifact\rdblquote  on the card\rquote s type line. They were artifacts that had activated abilities that don\rquote t include the tap symbol. Cards that were printed with the term \ldblquote poly artifact\rdblquote  now simply use \ldblquote artifact.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Postcombat\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 The second main phase in each turn is called the postcombat main phase. If an effect causes a turn to have an extra combat phase and another main phase, the additional one is also a postcombat main phase. See rule 305, \ldblquote Main Phase.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Power\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 The number before the slash printed on the lower right corner of a creature card is its power. See rule 208, \ldblquote Power/Toughness.\rdblquote \par      Creatures that attack or block assign combat damage equal to their power. See rule 310, \ldblquote Combat Damage Step.\rdblquote \par      Some creature cards have power represented by * instead of a number. The object has a characteristic-setting ability that sets its power according to some stated condition. The * is 0 while the object isn\rquote t in play.\par }\pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 {\insrsid2701857      A noncreature permanent has no power, even if it\rquote s a card with a power printed on it (such as a Licid that\rquote s become an Aura).\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Precombat\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 The first main phase in each turn is called the precombat main phase. See rule 305, \ldblquote Main Phase.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Prevention Effect\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Effects that prevent something from happening replace it with \ldblquote do nothing.\rdblquote  (See rule 419, \ldblquote Replacement and Prevention Effects.\rdblquote ) A prevention effect must be active before the event it\rquote s intended to prevent.\par      Effects that prevent a specific amount of damage act as \ldblquote shields\rdblquote  and stay active until that amount of damage has been prevented or the turn ends. The damage doesn\rquote t have to be dealt by a single source or all at once.\par }\pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 {\insrsid2701857      Effects that prevent the next damage from a specific source apply the next time that source would deal damage, regardless of the amount. These effects expire when the turn ends. See rule 419.8, \ldblquote Sources of Damage.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Priority\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 The player who has the option to play a spell or ability at any given time has priority. See rule 408, \ldblquote Timing of Spells and Abilities.\rdblquote \par      Each time a spell, an ability (other than a mana ability), or combat damage resolves, and at the beginning of most phases and steps, the active player receives priority. If a player has priority when he or she plays a spell, ability, or land, or takes a special action, he or she receives priority afterward. When a player passes in a two-player game, his or her opponent receives priority.\par      If all players pass in succession, the spell, ability, or combat damage on top of the stack resolves or, if the stack is empty, the phase or step ends.\par      Each time a player would get priority, all applicable state-based effects resolve first as a single event (see rule 420). Then, if any new state-based effects have been generated, they resolve as a single event. This process repeats until no more applicable state-based effects are generated. Then triggered abilities are added to the stack (see rule 410). These steps repeat in order until no further state-based effects or triggered abilities are generated.\par }\pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 {\insrsid2701857      In the Two-Headed Giant multiplayer variant, teams rather than individual players have priority. See rule 606, \ldblquote Two-Headed Giant Variant.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Protection\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Protection is a static ability, written \ldblquote Protection from [quality].\rdblquote  See rule 502.7, \ldblquote Protection.\rdblquote \par      A permanent with protection can\rquote t be targeted by spells with the stated quality and can\rquote t be targeted by abilities from a source with the stated quality.\par      A permanent with protection can\rquote t be enchanted by Auras that have the stated quality. Such Auras attached to the permanent with protection will be put into their owners\rquote  graveyards as a state-based effect. (See rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects.\rdblquote )\par      A permanent with protection can\rquote t be equipped by Equipment that has the stated quality. Such Equipment becomes unattached from that permanent, but remains in play. (See rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects.\rdblquote )\par      Any damage that would be dealt to a permanent with protection from sources having that quality is prevented.\par }\pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 {\insrsid2701857      If a creature with protection attacks, it can\rquote t be blocked by creatures that have the stated quality.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Provoke\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Provoke is a triggered ability. \ldblquote Provoke\rdblquote  means \ldblquote Whenever this creature attacks, you may choose to have target creature defending player controls block this creature this combat if able. If you do, untap that creature.\rdblquote  See rule 502.29, \ldblquote Provoke.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Public Information (Informal)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Some information within a }{\b\insrsid2701857 Magic}{\insrsid2701857  game is known by all players. For example, permanents in play, spells and abilities on the stack, and cards in graveyards are all public information. The number of cards in players\rquote  libraries and hands is also public information, even though contents of those libraries and hands are hidden information. See also Hidden Information.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Put Into Play\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 If an effect instructs a player to put an object into play, that object is not considered \ldblquote played.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Rampage\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Rampage is a triggered ability. \ldblquote Rampage N\rdblquote  means \ldblquote When this creature becomes blocked, it gets +N/+N until end of turn for each creature blocking it beyond the first.\rdblquote  See rule 502.12, \ldblquote Rampage.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Random\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 If a spell, ability, or effect requires a player to choose something at random, that player can use any method of making a random choice (rolling dice, flipping a coin, and so on). The outcome must be truly random.\par \par Recover\par }{\insrsid2701857\charrsid544042 Recover }{\insrsid2701857\charrsid544042 is a triggered ability that functions only while the card with recover is in a player\rquote s graveyard. \ldblquote Recover [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote }{\insrsid2701857\charrsid544042 When a creature is put into your graveyard from play, you may pay [cost]. If you do, return this card from your graveyard to your hand. Otherwise, remove this card from the game.}{\insrsid2701857 \rdblquote  See rule 502.55, \ldblquote Recover.\rdblquote }{\insrsid2701857\charrsid544042 \par }{\insrsid2701857 \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Redirect (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Some older cards were printed with the term \ldblquote redirect\rdblquote  to describe the act of dealing damage to a different player or creature than originally specified by a spell, ability, or combat-damage assignment, without changing the source or type of damage. In general, cards that were printed with the term \ldblquote redirect\rdblquote  now create replacement effects that modify where the damage will be dealt. \ldblquote Redirect\rdblquote  is still used informally to describe what these replacement effects do.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Regenerate\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Regeneration is a destruction-replacement effect. \ldblquote Regenerate [permanent]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote The next time [permanent] would be destroyed this turn, instead remove all damage from it, tap it, and (if it\rquote s in combat) remove it from combat.\rdblquote  Because it\rquote s a replacement effect, it must be active before the attempted destruction event. Abilities that trigger from damage being dealt still trigger even if the permanent regenerates. See rule 419.6b.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Reminder Text\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Reminder text appears after a keyword ability printed on a card and on cards that might otherwise be commonly misunderstood. Reminder text is text that is italicized and in parentheses in the text box of a card. This text provides a summary of the game rule or clarifies what the card does, but it isn\rquote t itself considered rules text. See rule 207.2.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Removed from Combat\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 An attacking or blocking creature is removed from combat if it leaves play (such as by being destroyed or removed from the game), if it regenerates (see rule 419.6b), if its controller changes, if it stops being a creature, or if an effect removes it from combat. A creature that is removed from combat stops being an attacking or blocking creature and can no longer assign combat damage or have combat damage assigned to it. Any combat damage that\rquote s already on the stack assigned to or by the creature will still resolve normally. See rule 306.2 and rule 310.4a.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Removed from the Game\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 A card removed from the game is out of play. The effect that removed the card may specify a way for it to return. Some objects use the expression \ldblquote set aside\rdblquote  for situations in which a card removed from the game can return to play. See rule 217.7, \ldblquote Removed from the Game.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Replacement Effect\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 A replacement effect is a type of continuous effect that \ldblquote watches\rdblquote  for a specified event and replaces it with a different one. See rule 419, \ldblquote Replacement and Prevention Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Replicate\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Replicate is a keyword that represents two abilities. The first is a static ability that functions while the spell is on the stack. The second is a triggered ability that functions while the spell is on the stack. \ldblquote Replicate [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote As an additional cost to play this spell, you may pay [cost] any number of times\rdblquote  and \ldblquote When you play this spell, if a replicate cost was paid for it, copy it for each time its replicate cost was paid. If the spell has any targets, you may choose new targets for any number of the copies.\rdblquote  See rule 502.52, \ldblquote Replicate.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Requirement\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 A requirement to attack or block is any effect that forces one or more creatures to attack or block. All attacks and blocks must still be legal. See rule 500, \ldblquote Legal Attacks and Blocks.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Resolve\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 When a spell or ability on top of the stack resolves, its controller carries out the instructions printed on the card, in the order written. When combat damage resolves, it\rquote s dealt as previously assigned to the fullest extent possible. See rule 413, \ldblquote Resolving Spells and Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Respond, Response (Informal)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 A player can choose to play an instant spell or activated ability when something else is already on the stack, rather than waiting for the earlier spell or ability to resolve first. The spell or ability is said to be played \ldblquote in response to\rdblquote  the earlier spell or ability. See rule 408, \ldblquote Timing of Spells and Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Restriction\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 A restriction on attacking or blocking is any effect that could prevent a creature from attacking or blocking. All attacks and blocks must still be legal. See rule 500, \ldblquote Legal Attacks and Blocks.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Reveal\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 To reveal an object is to show that object to all players. If a one-shot effect reveals a card, the card is returned to its former state after all players have seen it. If the cost to play a spell or ability includes revealing a card, the card remains revealed from the time the spell or ability is announced until it leaves the stack.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Ripple\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857\charrsid13311750 Ripple is a triggered ability that functions only while the card with ripple is on the stack. \ldblquote Ripple N\rdblquote  means \ldblquote When you play this spell, you may reveal the top N cards of your library, or, if there are fewer than N cards in your library, you may reveal all the cards in your library. }{\insrsid2701857\charrsid1265978 If you reveal cards from your library this way, you may play any of those cards }{\insrsid2701857\charrsid13311750 with the same name as this spell without paying their mana costs, then put all revealed cards not played this way on the bottom of your library in any order.\rdblquote }{\insrsid2701857  See rule 502.56, \ldblquote Ripple.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Rules Text\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 An object\rquote s rules text defines many of that object\rquote s properties. Changing an object\rquote s rules text changes the object\rquote s properties.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 Sacrifice\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2701857 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2701857 To sacrifice a permanent, its controller moves it from the in-play zone directly to its owner\rquote s graveyard. A player can\rquote t sacrifice something that isn\rquote t a permanent, or something that\rquote s a permanent he or she doesn\rquote t control. If an effect instructs a player to sacrifice a permanent that he or she doesn\rquote t control, nothing happens. Sacrificing a permanent doesn\rquote t destroy it, so regeneration or other effects that replace destruction can\rquote t affect it.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\l